text:
This was a good read, but I think the current #Ethereum culture is somewhat different at the higher levels in terms of development vs what is actually happening on chain.

Pluralism would be great, like really, but today the game is mostly about stealing TVL from left and right, deploying the same copy paste code all over the places, asking millions in STABLES for such deployments.

When there is no composability, people will deploy the copy pasted solutions over and over again. When there are no cross L2 guarantees in the system, it is super hard and costly to create and maintain bridges, nobody wants that, and nobody uses that. 0.01% of crypto people, maybe. They will rather go through a CEX.

Pluralism would be the must for #blockchain and it happens when COMPOSABILITY IS BUILT INTO THE PROTOCOL. Where it is common sense to build on top of an existing deployed solution, and not copy paste deploy and create new liquidity pools for example.

If you want pluralism you have to build the primitives which enable that. Execution matters, scaling matters, access to DeFi for billions matter.

L2s can exist on scalable, decentralised chains as #MultiversX as well, and they are much better. Built in composability towards the mainchain, towards other chains and towards other SovereignChains as well. This is what application specific chains should look like. This is how #SovereignChains are thought of.

Be part of the movement. Be a builder and let‚Äôs make this real. Finally build why and how it matters.

text:
Today I was listening to an interview of @sunnya97 about BitcoinL2s and Osmosis. One thing strikes me which is actually pretty true: there is no ONE big, well researched, well respected bridge between $BTC and #Ethereum and as SunnyA said, it might be because Ethereum wanted to take the crown, make $ETH the most important asset.

I am speaking here especially about a well funded bridge and interoperability layer between the 2 biggest chains. It is missing, it is not in the focus. Tribalism, fights, clearly not driving towards the same goal. A lot of attacks left and right.

Now following the same pattern, and watching the L2 scenes, although it is on the narrative of Ethereum, but there is no enshrined help at all for better integrations, no precompiles (which would be so simple to do, for all the prominent L2s). Also, there is still no seamless composability between L2 and L1, like why? Really really why?

The result, Uniswap deployed in most of the L2s, same with other big dApps, a lot of copy paste, nonsense use of time, energy and money. This is definitely not to accelerate Ethereum, and definitely not so aligned as a lot say so.

It is rather easy to go into an L2, but it is complicated to go out. Actually easy for developers who know what to do, fairly complicated for average persons.

Again, why is composability deleted from the dictionary? When it was one of the most important primitives Ethereum had in the ICO era till 2020 approximately. Asking these questions reveal the true nature of things.

#SovereignChain stack can change this, bring back composability to the space. Why not? Wouldn‚Äôt it be better?

text:
Do you know what's bothering people like @0xMert_, @ChainLinkGod or @Fiskantes about this Algorand ad?

It's because they can't admit that $ETH and $SOL (to name just a few) are huge barriers delaying mass adoption and repelling many potential users.

#Ethereum is a drag.
#Solana is a drag.

Crypto adoption definitely won't happen if such flawed chains are always being put in the spotlight.

We need all these silent users, often frustrated with crypto because of these chains, to know that there are other better options - like Algorand or others - much more suitable for them.

You can't expect people to use technology that isn't flawless in every way: gas fees, security issues, lack of scalability, failed on-chain transactions, downtime, fork, congestion, etc. are all major friction points that should not be minimized.

The fact that so many people are triggered by a simple sarcastic video is a clear indication of the profound unease within our ecosystem today.

#Algorand was designed by one of the brightest minds in the world, whose work is utilized by most chains today, with the specific aim of supporting mass adoption.

$ALGO deserves to be highlighted.

If the adoption of our ecosystem matters to you, then let's all collaborate together and stop bashing chains that are fit for purpose for the benefit of others, which are definitely not.

https://t.co/PfTZBwLZA1

author.name: Whale Insider

text:
We are so thrilled to confirm that the SEC has approved, pursuant to Section 19(b) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, our exchange partner CBOE‚Äôs proposed rule change to list and trade a @vaneck_us spot #Ethereum ETF on the CBOE! ü•≥üöÄ

TLDR: We expect the improved political backdrop will lead to further victories for digital asset investors & developers, via new laws & in the courts, that draw investment to #Bitcoin, Ethereum and other open-source blockchain software.

We applaud this decision, as we believe the evidence clearly shows that #ETH is a decentralized commodity, not a security.  ETH‚Äôs status as a commodity has now been recognized in a variety of circumstances, including the CFTC's regulation of ETH futures, public statements by Commission officials, rulings by federal courts, and now, hopefully, this ETF.

The high degree of correlation between ETH spot prices and CME Ethereum futures prices, similar to the correlation seen with Bitcoin, proved that the spot ETH market is tightly linked to the regulated futures market. This tight linkage supports the listing of spot ETH ETFs, as it allows for the market surveillance the SEC requires. Additionally, the presence of liquid, regulated ETH futures trading on the CME and the approval of ETFs tracking those futures demonstrated to all neutral observers that Ethereum meets the same criteria as Bitcoin for an ETF holding the spot asset. The SEC approved the listing of spot Bitcoin ETFs based on these exact criteria, and we have long believed that Ethereum warrants the same treatment.

Any claim that Ethereum's move to proof-of-stake has turned it into a security, or that staking itself is a securities transaction is misguided and harmful to innovation. Proof-of-stake is simply an alternative consensus mechanism to proof-of-work mining - it does not fundamentally alter Ethereum's decentralized nature or transform ETH into a security issued by a central entity. Since the DAO hack in 2016, Ethereum has become highly decentralized, with no centralized issuer or promoter controlling a material supply or percentage of validators. The Ethereum Foundation's ETH holdings have steadily declined to just 0.30% of the circulating supply, and Vitalik Buterin holds around 0.23%. This widespread distribution of ETH contradicts the idea of it being a security issued by a common enterprise.

We have also heard arguments that Ethereum‚Äôs transition to proof-of-stake (PoS) was a securities transaction. This misunderstands the decentralized nature of Ethereum‚Äôs governance. Ethereum‚Äôs transition to PoS was driven by social consensus, involving broad community discussions, transparent development processes, and voting mechanisms within a decentralized network. This contrasts sharply with traditional financial systems, where decisions are made by centralized entities or a small group of registered stakeholders. Changes in Ethereum are proposed through Ethereum Improvement Proposals (EIPs), debated publicly, and adopted only with widespread community support, ensuring no central authority controls the network. This decentralized, community-driven process highlights that Ethereum remains a decentralized commodity, not a security, as its evolution reflects the collective agreement of its diverse global participants.
 
As the UK Prime Minister on this topic just recently said: ‚ÄúWe are pro-open source. Open-source drives innovation. It creates start-ups. It creates communities. There must be a very high bar for any restrictions on open source.‚Äù

Many traditional finance market participants may not fully understand that ETH is not just a speculative asset but has extensive real-world utility underpinning a vibrant decentralized application ecosystem. Ethereum supports over 270 million unique user addresses and processes an average of 1.2 million transactions daily. On-chain value settlements exceeded $2.8 trillion over the last year, compared to global remittances of $860B, PayPal volumes of $1.5 trillion, and Visa network volume of $15 trillion. Ethereum boasts a robust developer community, with more than 2,300 monthly active developers contributing to 113,000 distinct Githib repositories. Thanks to the network effects from this decentralized community, Ethereum has become the foundational layer for a vast ecosystem of over 3,000 applications, including financial services, games and collectibles. Its smart contract functionality enables automated lending/borrowing, decentralized exchanges, NFT marketplaces, play-to-earn games, and tokenization of real-world assets. Major companies like Reddit, Ubisoft, Nike, and Visa have launched Ethereum-based projects. Regulating Ethereum NFTs differently from physical collectibles like baseball cards or Rolex watches is often absurd - both represent unique digital/physical scarcity and ownership. A Bored Ape Yacht Club NFT and a rare 1952 Topps Mickey Mantle rookie card can serve similar purposes as status symbols and stores of value. But governance structures like those enabled by Ethereum underpin much of the innovation happening in open-source databases, including real-world asset tokenization. Stifling this utility through misguided regulation would hamper technological progress and drive those talented entrepreneurs overseas.

The situation has been made even more confusing by the inconsistent stances taken by different U.S. regulators. While the SEC has recently declined to clarify ETH‚Äôs status, the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC) allowed Ether futures products to trade as commodities. The Chairman of the CFTC has stated repeatedly under oath that ETH is a commodity. Even the SEC's own guidance has stated that a digital asset may transition away from being a security as it becomes sufficiently decentralized over time, though critical details are lacking. Adding to the contradictions, just last week the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Southern District of New York unveiled an indictment that referred to Ethereum as a "decentralized" blockchain. Needless to say, this regulatory discord has fostered harmful uncertainty and, contrary to the SEC's mandate of capital formation, has inflicted a lot of pain in the market.

That‚Äôs why today feels particularly sweet to VanEck, the first traditional ETF issuer to file for both Bitcoin & Ethereum ETFs. It is so encouraging to observe the growing bipartisan support for digital assets in DC, reflecting widespread voter input, & culminating in today's ETF news and this week's congressional repeal of SAB 121, an accounting rule hostile to crypto that was enacted through unorthodox means. 

We expect this improved political backdrop will lead to further victories via new laws and in the courts that draw investment to Bitcoin, Ethereum and other open-source blockchain software.

Stay tuned for further updates. 

PS - we expect to go FIRST.

quote.text:
COINBASE SAYS ETHEREUM ETF APPROVAL MORE LIKELY THAN MOST BELIEVE - BULLISH ON $ETH PRICE POTENTIAL 

- Despite price-underperformance in 2022, leading CEX @Coinbase is bullish on $ETH‚Äôs price potential.

"Ether may have the potential to surprise to the upside in the coming months"

- Revealed in a research report this week, Coinbase highlighted to lack of #Ethereum supply side overhangs.

- While other assets suffer from major token unlocks or dumping from miners, $ETH is free of these ailments.

- Coinbase also states that Ethereum is really the heart of the existing DeFi landscape and this is unlikely to change any time soon‚Ä¶

"ETH's position as the center of decentralized finance (DeFi) is also unlikely to be displaced in our view due to the widespread adoption of the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) and its layer 2 innovations‚Äù

- What‚Äôs more, the exchange is more optimistic about the prospect of spot $ETH ETF approval in the United States, writing‚Ä¶

"We think the market may be underestimating the timing and odds of a potential approval, which leaves room for surprises to the upside‚Ä¶ Even if the first deadline of May 23, 2024 encounters a rejection, we think there is a high likelihood that litigation could reverse that decision‚Äù

- The combination of the above factors could spell a very exciting 2024 for the world‚Äôs second largest cryptocurrency.
